<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-04-08T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-04-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="518" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d518">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/986</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at London</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SRP1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Skinner</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-04-08">
                                        <hi rend="italic">April 8, 1915</hi>.</date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received April 9, 8 a.
                                    m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>If discharge of innocent cargo necessary to get at prize cargo
                                expenses of warehousing, reshipment and dues must be paid by <pb facs="0620" n="362" xml:id="pg_362"/> ship and if not
                                recoverable from ship then <hi rend="italic">pro rata</hi> from
                                cargo owners. April 1 I appealed to prize court for ruling which
                                would free ship and innocent cargo from all dues and expenses
                                arising from Government’s orders. President replies declining to
                                instruct Admiralty marshal except in consequence of proceedings in
                                form of judgment. Therefore unless representations are made to
                                Government, all detained ships will be required themselves to pay
                                costs resulting exclusively from orders of Admiralty.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_SRP1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Skinner</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>